The offset is they no longer have to pay out 80% of the gross bookings to drivers. So definitively worse returns on invested capital but potentially more profit dollars.
In effect, why does autonomous not turn Uber from an asset-light two-sided platform (a great business model) into a rent-by-the-mile rental car business (a not so good business model)?

Today, drivers bring their own (or lease their own) vehicles, making Uber asset-light. But in an autonomous world, there are no drivers to exploit, so Uber must deploy its own autonomous fleet, which is very capital intensive.

Uber is a classic two-sided network with cross-side network effects: the more riders there are the more drivers it attracts, and the more drivers there are, the better the experience for riders. Does this go away with autonomous?
Do autonomous cars make ride-hailing platforms like Uber better businesses or worse businesses?

There are obviously huge implications for logistics (especially I think last mile), real estate/urban planning (public parking, garages), car ownership (0/1 car per fam?), auto insurance (fewer accidents), municipal budgets (lower traffic ticket revs), pollution (> miles driven)

Massive increase in road supply lowers costs for transportation-intensive goods and services and increase labor mobility, driving expansion of suburbs & hollowing out of urban centers, and decentralization of manufacturing & expansion of inland cities far away from ports.
What’s the impact of this? Look at construction of the US interstate highway system in 1950s, Germany 1930s, or China from 2000s-now.
Thus, I think autonomous vehicles will have the same effect as adding a large supply of new roads across the entire network.

This is also true for building mass transit. Building mass transit does not reduce traffic. Some drivers switch to mass transit, but this causes others to drive more. Congestion stays the same (but throughput increases).
There’s almost a perfect relationship between an X% increase in supply of roads and Y% increase in miles driven. Seminal paper on this topic here:

There's a corollary: contrary to popular (layman’s) belief, adding lanes to highways and building new roads does not reduce congestion. Instead, new supply of roads creates new demand for driving, e.g. living farther from work, driving instead of walking, more frequent trips, etc
In reality, driving demand is fairly elastic. As autonomous vehicles reduce congestion, people will drive more, increasing congestion again.

Autonomous cars will get in fewer accidents, travel at faster speeds, and have denser spacing, thereby reducing traffic all else equal (see interesting demo below). However, this is ONLY true if we hold the demand for driving constant.
Many think autonomous vehicles will reduce/eliminate traffic. I think this is wrong.
